<h1><span id="Open_Sicilian">Open Sicilian</span></h1>
<p>Black's 2...d6 gives him the option of several popular attacking lines, controls the e5 square, supports the c-pawn and activates his queen's bishop.
</p><p>White's rationale for playing 2. Nf3 was to support a 3. d4 advance which he may now play. His best alternative to this, for rapid development, is 3. Bb5+, forcing Black to block the check with a minor piece that would then be pinned to the king. Swashbuckling players might be tempted by 3. b4, planning an unopposed d4 when the Black c-pawn is diverted to b4.
</p>
<p><b>1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6</b>
